skills kinds of nouns we all know what
is a noun now let's learn what are
different kinds of noun nouns are a four
types they are collective abstract
countable and uncountable nouns
[Music]
collective noun a collective noun
denotes number of person or thing taken
together and spoken of as one whole for
example I found a bunch of keys the
cattle were grazing in the field an army
of soldiers marched in the parade
words like Bunch
cattle army are called collective nouns
in this example bunch describes the
collection of things that is keys here
cattle describes the collection of
animals that is cows in this example
army describes the collection of people
that is soldiers now let's look at some
more examples a flock of birds a flock
of birds came to the sanctuary crowd of
people
the police dispersed the crowd of people
a fleet of ships a fleet of ships was
found in the middle of the sea
a herd of giraffes I saw a herd of
giraffes running in the forest a pride
of lions a pride of lions surrounded a
deer now let's learn abstract noun nouns
that denote the qualities in people
animals or things are called abstract
nouns for example the firemen showed
great bravery laughs there is a great
tonic we should have patience while
waiting in a queue who doesn't like the
smell of a rose
words like bravery laughter patience
smell are called abstract nouns here are
some more examples of abstract nouns the
judgment was given yesterday there was a
theft in my neighbor's house I like the
softness of this fabric we should have
courage to face problems Beauty needs no
ornaments darkness falls
soon after sunset honesty is the best
policy in these examples
words like judgment theft softness
courage Beauty darkness and honesty are
all examples of abstract nouns now let's
learn countable nouns countable nouns
are easy to recognize they are things
that we can count for example then we
can count pens we can have one two three
or more pens here are some more examples
of countable nouns dog cat man bottle
box coin dollar table chair suitcase bag
these are all examples of countable
nouns as we can count them in numbers
countable nouns can be singular or
plural for example my dog is playing my
dogs are hungry we can use the
indefinite article a or an with
countable nouns for example a dog is an
animal when a countable noun is singular
we must use a word like a der by this
with a countable noun for example I want
an orange you should never say I want
orange another example you always say
where is my bottle and not where is
bottle when a countable noun is plural
we can use it alone for example I like
oranges bottles can break we can use
some and any with countable nouns for
example I've got some money have you got
any pens we can use a few and many with
countable nouns for example I've got a
few rupees I haven't got many pens
note people is countable people is the
plural of person we can count people for
example there is one person here there
are three people here you have learned
countable nouns now let's understand
uncountable nouns uncountable nouns are
substances concepts etc that we cannot
divide into separate elements we cannot
count them for example we cannot count
milk we can count bottles of milk or
liters of milk but we cannot count milk
itself here are some more examples of
uncountable nouns music art love
happiness rice sugar butter water these
are all examples of uncountable nouns we
do not usually use the indefinite
article a or and with uncountable nouns
we cannot say an information or a music
but we can say something of for example
a piece of news a bottle of water a
grain of rice etc we can use some and
any with uncountable nouns for example
I've got some money have you got any
rice we can use a little and much with
uncountable nouns
for example I've got a little money I
haven't got much rice note uncountable
nouns are also called
mass nouns this was a demonstration
